{% extends "base.html" %}

{% block help%}
<p>By default, when generating a Circos from data file(s), the interface is using predefined parameters and attributes to construct the image. For example, you can not select the filling color of histogram bins. However, there <em>is</em> a way to personalize your Circos! Here is how you do it:</p>
		<p><ol>
			<li>Generate a Circos from data file(s) using the interface</li>
			<li>Download the <font color="#0088cc">circos.zip</font> package of that Circos</li>
			<li>In any text editor sofware, open the appropriate <font color="#0088cc">.conf</font> files and modify them for the desired parameters/attributes
			    <br>
			    <em><b>Tip: </b>Modify the files directly from the package</em></li>
			<li>Upload the "new" package (it is actually the one downloaded with some modifications to its files) to the interface
			    <br>
			    <em><b>Tip: </b>In <font color="#0088cc">Generate a Circos</font>, select the <font color="#0088cc">From configuration files</font> option</em></li>
		</ol></p>
		<p>Since not everyone is familiar with Circos' configuration files, here are some tips and examples of modifications you could apply to your <font color="#0088cc">circos.zip</font> files. Feel free to experiment and play around!</p>
		<p>For more information, please refer to the Circos <a href="http://circos.ca/documentation/tutorials/" class="alert-link">tutorials</a>.</p>
		<br>		
		<center><h4>Circos generated by the interface with defaut parameters/attributes</h3></center>
		<center><p><em>Labels, Histogram, Scatter Plot, Heat Map, Tiles, Links</em></p></center>		
		<img class="media-object" src="{{ url_for('image', img='default.png')}}" alt="Normalized values" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; width:90%; height:90%" >
{% endblock %}

